<DOC><DOCNO> AP880525-0211 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 1709EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w BC-HouseDisclosures-Maryland     05-25 0616</FIRST><SECOND>BC-House Disclosures-Maryland,x00</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are capsule summaries of the financialdisclosure forms filed by members of the House from Maryland for1987 and released Wednesday.   Income includes the House salary, honoraria earnings fromwriting and speeches and other income such as dividends andinterest.   Earnings by the representatives' spouses and dependents are notincluded in the income figure.   The asset and liability figures for the representatives do notinclude holdings and liabilities of spouses and dependents.   Representatives are permitted to keep honoraria earnings fromspeeches and writings up to 30 percent of their salary. For nearlyall members, their salary was $89,500 at the end of 1987. Thespeaker of the House was paid at the annualized rate of $115,000and the Democratic and Republican leaders were paid at theannualized rate of $99,500.   Many members receive honoraria above the limit and donate theexcess to charity.   In their financial disclosure forms, representatives are allowedto list income, assets and liabilities by ranges instead ofspecific figures. However, some representatives provide specificfigures.   In their listing of assets, representatives do not have toinclude their personal residences and vehicles. Gifts, thoughlisted, are not counted in income figure given here.</TEXT><TEXT>   BENJAMIN L. CARDIN   Income: $216,612-$282,607.   Honoraria: $6,550, all given to charity.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $535,012-$1.035 million.   Liabilities: None.   Cardin, a lawyer and former speaker of the Maryland House,received $20,500 in salary from a law firm he owns as well as morethan $28,000 in payments for legal services he performed before hewas elected to Congress in 1986. He also received $20,000 indeferred compensation and $2,785 in pension benefits from the state.</TEXT><TEXT>   HELEN DELICH BENTLEY   Income: $98,435-$103,993.   Honoraria: $8,950.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $35,005-$115,000.   Liabilities: None.</TEXT><TEXT>   BEVERLY BYRON   Income: $114,520-$138,518.   Honoraria: $16,800.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $165,003-$445,000.   Liabilities: $95,004-$250,000.   Byron, a supporter of President Reagan's defense buildup, was apopular speaker among defense contractors, among them McDonaldDouglas Co., Northrop Corp. and Lockheed-California Co.</TEXT><TEXT>   KWEISI MFUME   Income: $101,016-102,515.   Honoraria: $3,950.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $50,001-100,000.   Liabilities: None.</TEXT><TEXT>   STENY H. HOYER   Income: $181,881-$220,878.   Honoraria: None.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $270,002-$320,000 and up.   Liabilities: $15,001-$50,000.   Hoyer's outside income came from his law practice and a house inNantucket, Mass., which yielded $15,001 to $50,000 in rent.</TEXT><TEXT>   ROY DYSON   Income: $104,484-$119,483.   Honoraria: $12,000, of which an undisclosed amount was given tocharity.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $120,005-$310,000.   Liabilities: up to $5,000.</TEXT><TEXT>   CHARLES T. McMILLEN   Income: $287,999-$549,483.   Honoraria: $19,900, of which $400 was given to charity.   Gifts: Listed as more than $100.   Assets: $920,022-$2.018 million and up.   Liabilities: $260,006-$580,000.   McMillen, who played 11 years in the National BasketballAssociation, listed $15,000 from the Washington Bullets and $15,000from the Atlanta Hawks as deferred salary, and claimed $6,600 fromthe NBA itself as part of the severance payment agreement in theunion contract when he quit to run for Congress.   He said he would receive $11,000 a year for five years beginningin 1997 as his portion of the NBA's licensing agreement _ the useof his name and picture on products sold by the league.   He also received $2,500 as a percentage of income fromsubscribers of Star Channel, a television cable company inCharlotte, N.C., for which he did marketing work in 1982 as amember of the Hawks.   McMillen also said he would receive an annual pension of $16,500per year from the NBA when he reaches 50 _ he turns 36 on Thursday.   As a gift, he said he received U.S. Open Tennis Tournamenttickets from the Phillip Morris Co. valued at more than $100.</TEXT><TEXT>   CONSTANCE A. MORELLA   Income: $108,084-$118,083.   Honoraria: $2,600.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $160,004-$205,000   Liabilities: $30,002-$100,000</TEXT></DOC>